<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-031-282 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 432 531</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 21 1991 v8 n42 p5(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lotus fixes 1-2-3/W, posts hot Q3. (Lotus Development Corp.andO;releases Lotus 1-2-3 for Windows 1.0a, earnings up by 151 percentin the third quarter 1991)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fisher, Susan; Ferranti, Marc.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Lotus Development Corp showed a 151 percent rise in earning and a37 percent rise in sales for the 3rd qtr 1991 compared to the sameperiod in 1990.andP;  Earnings totalled $21.5 million on sales of$218.8 million.andP;  Sales of upgrades, spurred by Lotus' move intothe direct-marketing field, added $40 million to the sales total,more than what analysts expected.andP;  Lotus is already upgrading itsLotus 1-2-3 for Windows which had been plagued with bugs in thescreen-repaint and Macro facilities, and has file compatibilityproblems with other 1-2-3 products.andP;  Lotus is offering theupgrade, Lotus 1-2-3 for Windows 1.0a, free to registered users ofLotus 1-2-3 for Windows and shipping it to stores to replaceVersion 1.0.andP;  The new release is not expected to cause a jump in1-2-3 for Windows' sales, as most analysts feel there are betterspreadsheets for Windows on the market.andP;  Windows programs do notgenerate a large volume of initial sales.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (Finance).andO;Ticker:    LOTS.andO;Product:   Lotus 1-2-3 for Windows (Spreadsheet software) (Product defects,recall, etc.)andO;Lotus 1-2-3 for Windows 1.0a (Spreadsheet software) (Marketing)Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (Computerprograms).andO;Topic:     ProfitGrowthRevenueDefectsSoftware PublishersCompatibilitySpreadsheetsSoftware packagesThird QuarterFinancial Report.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Susan FisherandM;and Marc FerrantiandM;Lotus Development Corp. last week reported a healthy third quarter and movedto answer user concerns about 1-2-3 for Windows by announcing an update ofthe spreadsheet.andM;The Cambridge, Mass., company reported earnings of $21.5 million on sales of$218.8 million for the third quarter, which ended Sept.andP;  28.andM;That's a 151 percent increase for earnings and a 37 percent hike in salescompared with the depressed results Lotus reported for the same period a yearago.andM;Upgrades contributed about $40 million in revenue for the quarter, a higherfigure than many financial analysts expected.andP;  Lotus has invigorated itsupgrade business by employing direct-marketing tactics similar to those ofrival Borland International Inc., according to Rick Sherlund, an analyst forthe investment firm of Goldman, Sachs andamp; Co. in New York.andM;&quot;The extent to which the Windows product has been off to a slow start hasbeen offset by strong sales of Lotus' traditional 1-2-3 for DOS products,specifically 2.3 and 3.1,&quot; Sherlund said.andM;Lotus officials said 1-2-3 for Windows has been selling well and meetingexpectations.andM;The product's update, 1-2-3 for Windows version 1.0a, corrects bugs inscreen-repaint and Macro Transcript facilities, improves compatibility with1-2-3 for DOS release 2.3 and 3.1 files, and adds the ability to readMicrosoft Excel 3.0 files, according to company officials.andM;Users of the first Windows version reported having trouble displaying ashaded range of cells and repainting the screen after deleting rows of aworksheet while in perspective (three-dimensional) mode.andM;Compatibility FixandM;Version 1.0a corrects these display problems and enables users to bring infonts from release 2.3 and 3.1 files so they look identical, pixel for pixel,in Windows, said Lotus officials.andM;The update also fixes the Macro Transcript facility, which in the firstversion did not correctly record the full sequence of keystrokes.andM;Users who order 1-2-3 for Windows directly from Lotus will receive version1.0a.andP;  All registered 1-2-3 for Windows users will be offered the new versionfree of charge.andP;  Users who registered through resellers will be sent a cardasking them to specify the disk format they use.andP;  Version 1.0a will be instores within a week or so, according to company officials.andM;Doctoring kinks in the program may assuage some 1-2-3 customers, but it maynot be enough to stimulate a wave of new sales, some analysts said.andM;&quot;I don't think it's a bug-fix issue,&quot; said Bruce Lapatkin, an analyst at SanFrancisco investment firm Hambrecht andamp; Quist.andP;  &quot;There are better products inthe market -- namely, Microsoft's Excel.&quot;andM;However, both analysts and resellers say it's too early to know how the Lotusspreadsheet will fare over time.andM;&quot;It's a reasonable start.andP;  You can't expect a Windows product to get off to astart the way a DOS product does,&quot; said Timothy McCollum, an analyst with theinvestment firm of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New York.andP;  &quot;The fourthquarter is the telling quarter.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>